sql:
SELECT AVG(sample_count) AS average_samples_per_experiment
FROM (
  SELECT experiment_id, COUNT(sample_id) AS sample_count
  FROM samples
  GROUP BY experiment_id
);

external_knowledge:
- 'reached the end of their journey' refers to experiments with a status of 'completed';
- 'latest samples' refers to the most recent version of each sample;
- 'experiment version dates' are the dates when the most recent versions of the experiments were created.

- 'Completed' refers to experiments that have been fully executed and concluded.;
- 'Principal Investigator' is the lead researcher responsible for an experiment.;
- 'Approved' sample versions are those that have been reviewed and accepted.;
- 'Detailed descriptions' refer to version descriptions longer than 100 characters.;
- 'Last three years' refers to the period from January 1, 2020, to December 31, 2022.

- 'High-quality' refers to a data quality score or grade that is considered reliable and accurate;
- 'Controlled' samples are those that are managed under standardized conditions to ensure consistency and reliability of the results;
- The mean value is a statistical measure representing the average of a set of data points.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(*) 
FROM sample_versions 
WHERE version_status = 'approved';

external_knowledge:
- The latest versions of experiments and samples are used to ensure the most up-to-date data is considered;
- The quality score of samples is part of the data but not directly used in determining the top researcher;
- The researcher with the highest number of experiments is considered the most active.

- 'average mean value' is calculated as the mean of all data points associated with a sample;
- 'overall average mean value' is the mean of the average mean values of all samples;
- 'Drug A' is a specific treatment applied to the samples;
- 'Tissue' refers to the source of the sample.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(*) AS experiment_count
FROM experiments
WHERE status = 'completed';

external_knowledge:
- "Principal Investigator" refers to the lead researcher responsible for the experiment;
- "Frozen" storage conditions imply that the samples are kept at a low temperature to preserve their integrity;
- "A high standard" refers to an average quality score greater than 0.8.

- "blossomed into more than five unique samples" refers to experiments with more than 5 samples;
- "rich tapestry of over 100 data points" refers to each sample having more than 100 data points;
- "robust set of more than two permissions" refers to each sample having more than 2 permissions;
- "diverse version history of over three iterations" refers to each sample having more than 3 versions;
- "well-documented access log of more than 10 events" refers to each sample having more than 10 access events.

- 'Shining star' refers to the experiment with the highest rank;
- 'Reigns supreme' indicates the highest cumulative mean value;
- 'Cumulative mean value' is the sum of the mean values of all samples in the experiment.

- "top 3 most significant samples" refers to the samples with the highest average mean values;
- "average mean values" are calculated by averaging the mean values of the data associated with each sample;
- "access counts" represent the number of times each sample has been accessed.

- 'high-quality samples' refers to samples with a data quality score of 'high';
- 'instrument' refers to the source of the data being an instrument;
- 'completed' and 'archived' are statuses indicating that the experiment has been finished or stored for reference.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(data_id) 
FROM sample_data 
WHERE mean > (SELECT AVG(mean) FROM sample_data);

external_knowledge:
- 'Principal Investigator' is a key role in research, typically responsible for the overall management and direction of a research project;
- 'Completed' status indicates that the experiment has been finished and all data collection and analysis are complete;
- The average number of samples per experiment provides insight into the scale of the research conducted by each Principal Investigator.

- "wise sages" refers to researchers who have conducted experiments;
- "approved experimental scrolls" refers to experiments with approved versions;
- "files heavier than the average weight" refers to the average file size being greater than the overall average file size in the database.

- 'Compliant' means the experiment meets all regulatory standards;
- 'High average sample quality' refers to an average quality score greater than 0.5;
- 'Latest version' refers to the most recent version number of the sample.
